NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|However, I know although on this hand Bonnie will be dummy, she actually evaluates her hand as if she is declarer. This is a subtle part of Bergen evaluation that most people don't know. What Bergen means by "dummy points" is "dummy" is the person with the shorter trump.|
PG| ***** 46 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|On most hands, that is indeed the person who will actually be dummy. However, on transfer hands, it turns out that the person who will be declarer has the shorter trumps, so, for the purpose of hand evaluation, they must count dummy points.|
PG| ***** 47 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|And, similarly, the person who is dummy has the longer trumps, so evaluates as if they were declarer. One way to think of that is "count dummy points if you have the shorter trumps" BUT "count declarer points if you have the longer trumps." That is really what Bergen intended. |
PG| ***** 48 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|So Bonnie counts declarer points. To her original 6 she adds 1 for 5 hearts, adds 2 for singleton, and adds 1 for side club suit for a total of 10. As Boater only bid 3H, showing 15 or 16, that means they have 25 or 26. So Bonnie does not have a clear cut choice.|
PG| ***** 49 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|I think pass is slightly better, due to her quacks and bad heart suit, and only an 8-card fit but 4H is certainly not crazy and could work well. I pass because one of my bidding rules is to be conservative with an 8-card fit, aggressive with a 9-card fit. And since Boater did not super accept (jump to 3H over 2D), they have an 8 card fit. For that reason I would pass, but I would be worried about missing 4.|
